## Executive Summary

The European Commission’s Service for Foreign Policy Instruments is a
top-tier donor with a 2025 funding portfolio totaling approximately
\$201 million, showing strategic prioritization across seven global
regions with significant concentration in select areas. Its increasing
number of recipient countries—from under 8 in 2022 to nearly 26 in
2025—reflects a broadening geographic scope. Funding patterns reveal
moderate earmarking specificity aligned with foreign policy objectives,
yet transaction volumes are fewer and smaller compared to peers,
indicating funding volatility. Fundraisers should tailor proposals to
emphasize regional priorities, demonstrate adaptability to funding
fluctuations, and align with the donor’s evolving geopolitical focus to
maximize engagement opportunities.

## Geographic Shift

This alluvial chart displays the distribution of disbursement
percentages by the European Commission’s Service for Foreign Policy
Instruments across seven country groups from 2022 through 2025. Data
comprises 21 observations with funding shares ranging from 0.1% to

subsequent years have fewer, reflecting changing allocations. Four main

Notably, there is a visible shift in funding emphasis over time, as
represented by the flow thickness between country groups and years,

moderate with the interquartile range between 6.6% and 28.9%. This trend
underlines the need for proposal writers to consider these shifting
priorities to align funding requests with emerging focus areas.
Evaluations should monitor these changes to adjust program designs
accordingly, ensuring maximum alignment with donor funding patterns.

## Volatility

This line chart visualizes the funding volatility of the European
Commission’s Service for Foreign Policy Instruments by transaction date
and transaction value in US dollars. The data covers 147 transactions
from March 2023 to December 2025 with an average transaction value of
approximately 1.6 million USD spread over an average of 49 transactions
per year. Compared to a benchmark of the top 10 other donors, which show
a higher average transaction amount of 2.9 million USD and significantly
more frequent transactions averaging 371 per year, the European
Commission’s funding is less frequent and of lower value per
transaction. This pattern indicates a relatively sporadic funding
pattern, which may limit the stability and predictability of resources
for humanitarian operations. For proposal design and fundraising, this
suggests a need to ensure flexible programming able to adapt to funding
fluctuations. It also highlights an opportunity to advocate for
increased transaction volume or value to improve program stability and
impact. Overall, understanding this volatility is crucial for planning
sustainable engagement and resource allocation within funded projects.
